[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] The **1788–89 United States House of Representatives elections** were the first U.S.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] House of Representatives elections following the adoption of the Constitution of the United States.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] Each state set its own date for its congressional elections, ranging from November 24, 1788, to March 5, 1789, before or after the first session of the 1st United States Congress convened on March 4, 1789.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] They coincided with the election of George Washington as the first president of the United States.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] With the new form of government needing to be operational prior to the completion of the first national census, Article I, Section 2, Clause 3 of the U.S.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] Constitution set a temporary apportionment of seats.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] Among the original 13 states, 11 of them ratified the Constitution and elected 59 total representatives.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] North Carolina and Rhode Island did not ratify the Constitution until after the 1st Congress began, and consequently did not elect their representatives until 1790.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] Actual political parties did not yet exist, but new members of Congress were informally categorized as either "pro-Administration" (i.e., pro-Washington and pro-Hamilton) or "anti-Administration".
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] The first session of the first House of Representatives came to order in Federal Hall, New York City on March 4, 1789, with only thirteen members present.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] The requisite quorum (thirty members out of fifty-nine) was not present until April 1, 1789.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] The first order of business was the election of a Speaker of the House.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] On the first ballot, Frederick Muhlenberg was elected Speaker by a majority of votes.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] The business of the first session was largely devoted to legislative procedure rather than policy.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] Article I, Section 2, Clause 3 of the U.S.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] Constitution set a temporary congressional apportionment until the first national census was completed in 1790.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] In the 18th and much of the 19th century, each state set its own date for elections.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] In many years, elections were even held after the legal start of the Congress, although typically before the start of the first session.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] In the elections for the 1st Congress, five states held elections in 1788, electing a total of 29 Representatives, and six held elections in 1789, electing a total of 30 Representatives.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] Six seats were filled late because North Carolina and Rhode Island ratified the Constitution late.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] One pro-Administration representative resigned and the seat remained open at the end of the Congress.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] This was the first special election to the United States House of Representatives.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] Under the law at the time, each voter cast two votes for representative, at least one of whom had to be from a different county.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] Georgia had a mixed at-large/district system for the 1st Congress.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] Representatives were elected at-large, but for three district-based seats.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] Maryland had a mixed district/at-large system similar to Georgia's.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] Massachusetts required a majority vote, necessitating additional votes if no one won a majority.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] This was necessary in 4 of the districts.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] — **The Documentary History of the First Federal Elections: 1788-1790*.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] New Hampshire law required a winning candidate to receive votes from a majority of voters (16.7% of votes).
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] No candidate won such a majority on the first ballot, so a second ballot was held February 2, 1789.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] The election of all four representatives was contested, but the records that explained the precise grounds on which the election was contested have been lost due to the burning of Washington in the War of 1812.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] It is known to have related to questions of regularity and procedure.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] All four representatives' elections were ruled valid.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] New York held elections to the 1st Congress on March 3 and 4, 1789.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] They are retroactively numbered in this section.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] North Carolina ratified the Constitution late and thus elected representatives to the 1st Congress in 1790.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] Pennsylvania held elections to the 1st Congress on November 26, 1788.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] For this first election (and again in 1792 election for the 3rd Congress), Pennsylvania chose to elect all of its representatives on a single statewide general ticket, an attempt by the pro-Administration-majority legislature to prevent anti-Administration candidates from winning seats.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] Rhode Island ratified the Constitution late and thus elected representatives to the 1st Congress in 1790.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] An election to the United States House of Representatives was held in Pennsylvania on November 26, 1788, for the 1st Congress.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] The United States Constitution was adopted on September 17, 1787, by the Constitutional Convention in Philadelphia, and then ratified by the States.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] Pennsylvania's legislature ratified the Constitution on December 12, 1787, by a vote of 46–23.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] On July 8, 1788, the Congress of the Confederation passed a resolution calling the first session of the 1st United States Congress for March 4, 1789, to convene at New York City and the election of senators and representatives in the meanwhile by the States.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] Pennsylvania's legislature scheduled the election for November 26, 1788, and provided for it to be held on an at-large basis.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] This was an attempt by the Federalist-dominated legislature to prevent anti-Federalist Representatives from being elected in frontier districts.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] Both parties submitted tickets with 8 candidates each.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] The large German population in Pennsylvania tended to vote for German candidates, giving the Anti-Federalist Muhlenberg and Hiester enough votes to gain seats.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] The **1788 United States House of Representatives elections in South Carolina** were held on November 24 and 25, 1788 to select five Representatives for two-year terms from the state of South Carolina.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] The elections resulted in two candidates in support of Washington's administration and three candidates opposed to his policies.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Smith defeated two candidates in the first election of the 1st congressional district, known as the Charleston District.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Aedanus Burke defeated Robert Barnwell in the first election of the 2nd congressional district, known as the Beaufort-Orangeburg District.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Daniel Huger won the first election of the 3rd congressional district, known as the Georgetown-Cheraw District.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Thomas Sumter won the first election of the 4th congressional district, known as the Camden District.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Thomas Tudor Tucker won the first election of the 5th congressional district, known as the Ninety-Six District.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia] Congressional elections to the 1st United States Congress were held in Georgia on February 9, 1789, for the state's three congressional districts.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia] All elected representatives were members of the Anti-Administration political faction in Congress.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia] The Georgia Election Act of 1789 established a mixed at-large/district system for congressional elections.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia] Under the act, representatives were elected at-large on a general ticket but for three district-based seats, for which candidates were required to be residents.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia] Each voter was allowed to cast three votes, one for a candidate in each district.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia] Some candidates received votes in multiple districts.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia] The election returns were opened on February 26.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia] Only the returns of Richmond, Wilkes, Effingham, Chatham, Liberty, Burke, and Washington Counties were counted, as they had been received in time.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia] The returns from Greene, Glynn, and Camden Counties came in too late but were published anyways.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia] All elected representatives would've won with the returns of those counties included.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia] The Lower District was also known as the Eastern District or the First District.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia] Jackson led a Savannah-based political faction, referred to as the Jackson party, centered in Coastal Georgia.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia] The Middle District was also known as the Center District or the Second District.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-georgia] The Upper District was also known as the Western District or the Third District.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The **1796–97 United States House of Representatives elections** took place in the various states between August 12, 1796 (in North Carolina), and October 15, 1797 (in Tennessee).
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Each state set its own date for its elections to the House of Representatives.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The size of the House increased to 106 seats after Tennessee became the 16th U.S. state to join the union.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The first session of the 5th United States Congress was convened on May 15, 1797, at the proclamation of the new President of the United States, John Adams.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Since Kentucky and Tennessee had not yet voted, they were unrepresented until the second session began on November 13, 1797.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Gains for the Federalist Party provided the president with a reliable majority in support of his policies.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Many of the Federalist pick-ups in Congress came from the former Middle Colonies (New York, Pennsylvania, New Jersey, and Delaware).
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] New England remained heavily Federalist, whereas the South and West favored Democratic-Republican candidates.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Federalist trade and infrastructure policies found widespread approval in the Mid-Atlantic states during this era.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] With the growth of cities in Maryland, Pennsylvania, and New York, government intervention in the interest of industrialization and mercantilism became more attractive to voting citizens in these areas.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] During this period, each state fixed its own date for a congressional general election.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Elections to a Congress took place both in the even-numbered year before and in the odd-numbered year when the Congress convened.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In some states the congressional delegation was not elected until after the legal start of the Congress (on the 4th day of March in the odd-numbered year).
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Elections took place both in the even-numbered year before and in the odd-numbered year when a Congress convened.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In some states, the congressional delegation was not elected until after the legal start of the Congress (on the 4th day of March in the odd-numbered year).
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The 1st session of the 5th Congress ran May 15 – July 10, 1797, before the states of Kentucky and Tennessee had their elections, causing those states to be unrepresented in the 1st session.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Elections are sorted by election date, then by district.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] There were special and late elections to the 4th Congress in 1796.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] There were special and late elections to the 5th Congress in 1797.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Connecticut elected its seven representatives at-large on a general ticket.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Two of the four Democratic-Republicans were replaced by Federalists, bringing the Federalists from a 4–4 split to a 6–2 majority.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Massachusetts's electoral law required a majority for election, necessitating additional trials in three districts.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In 1796, New Hampshire had a single at-large district with 4 seats.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Each voter cast 4 votes and a majority of voters (12.5% of votes) was required to be elected.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Since only three candidates received a majority, a run-off was held between the candidates in fourth and fifth place to fill the remaining seat.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Rhode Island had an at-large district with two seats, each of which were elected separately.
[src:1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Due to Vermont's law requiring a majority to secure a congressional seat, the 1st district required three ballots to choose a winner.
